{"title_page": "Walter Hadwen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Walter Robert Hadwen \n| image      = Walter Hadwen.png \n|birth_date  = 3 August 1854\n|birth_place = [[Woolwich]] \n|death_date  = {{d-da|27 December 1932|3 August 1854}}\n|death_place = [[Gloucester]]\n| occupation = Physician, pharmaceutical chemist, writer}}\n\n'''Walter Robert Hadwen''' MD MRCS MRCP (3 August 1854, [[Woolwich]] \u2013 27 December 1932) was a [[Gloucester]] [[general practitioner]] and pharmaceutical chemist, president of the [[British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection]] (BUAV), and an [[Anti-vaccinationists|anti-vaccination]] campaigner known for his [[germ theory denialism|denial of the germ theory of disease]].\n\n==Biography==\nHadwen began his career as a [[pharmacist]] in [[Clapham]] then [[Somerset]], then subsequently trained as a doctor at [[Bristol University]]. After qualifying, he moved to Gloucester in 1896. Hadwen was recruited as a member of BUAV by its founder and then president [[Frances Power Cobbe]] who hired a private investigator to assess his credentials (he was a [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and total abstainer, had a reputation as a \"firebrand\" orator and was held in \"high local esteem\"). She subsequently selected him as her successor.<ref>Mitchell, Sally. (2004). ''Frances Power Cobbe: Victorian Feminist, Journalist, Reformer''. University of Virginia Press. p. 360. ISBN 0-8139-2271-2</ref>\n\nHe joined the [[Plymouth Brethren]] as an adult. He was a frequent speaker for the [[National Anti-Vaccination League]]. He was also a member of the [[London Association for the Prevention of Premature Burial]] (founded in 1896).\n\nHadwen stated that the \"modern germ theory is all bosh\".<ref>{{cite journal|year=1924|title=Verdict of Manslaughter Against Dr. Hadwen by Coroner's Jury|journal=[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082605828&view=1up&seq=54|volume=83|issue=14|pages=1090}}</ref>\n\n== Manslaughter trial ==\n\nIn 1924, having applied his rejection of the [[germ theory of disease]], and his refusal to use diphtheria anti-serum produced by inoculation of animals to the treatment of Nellie Burnham, a young girl, she died and he was tried for [[manslaughter]] by criminal [[medical negligence]].<ref>[[The Times]] up to and including 30 October 1924.</ref>  He was acquitted of all charges.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1924|title=Acquittal of Dr. Hadwen|journal=[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082605828&view=1up&seq=579|volume=83|issue=20|pages=1601}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications==\n\n* ''The Case Against Vaccination'', 1896\n*[https://archive.org/details/39002086340917.med.yale.edu/page/n2/mode/2up ''Smallpox at Gloucester: A Reply to Dr. Coupland\u2019s Report''], 1902. Reprinted from \"The Reformer,\" [[National Anti-Vaccination League]]: Gloucester.\n*[https://archive.org/details/debateonshouldvi00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''A Debate on Should Vivisection be Abolished?''], 1907\n*[https://archive.org/details/vivisectioncontr00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''A Vivisection Controversy''], 1911\n*[https://archive.org/details/experimentsonliv00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''Experiments on Living Animals, Useless and Cruel''], 1914\n*''The Difficulties of Dr. Deguerre'', 1926\n\nAbout\n*''Hadwen of Gloucester: Man, Medico, Martyr'', by Beatrice E. Kidd and M. Edith Richards, 1933, John Murray, London\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Vaccine controversy]]\n{{wikisource author}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.drhadwentrust.org/about-us/who-was-dr-hadwen Who was Dr Hadwen] Biography at Dr Hadwen Trust\n*''Frances Power Cobbe: Victorian Feminism, Journalist, Reformer'', Sally Mitchell, 2004, University of Virginia Press {{ISBN|0-8139-2271-2}}\n*''Bodily Matters: The Anti-Vaccination Movement in England, 1853-1907'', Nadja Durbach, 2005, Duke University Press, {{ISBN|0-8223-3423-2}}\n*Obituary, The Times, Saturday, 25 February 1933 John Murray, London, 1933\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soilandhealth.org/02/0201hyglibcat/020119hadwin/020119hadwenrallytalk.html SoilAndHealth.org] - 'The Case Against Vaccination', Walter Hadwen (25 January 1896)\n*[http://www.soilandhealth.org/02/0201hyglibcat/020119hadwin/020119hadwenmagazine.html SoilAndHealth.org] - ' The Fraud of Vaccination', Dr. Hadwen, ''Truth'', (3 January 1923)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hadwen, Walter}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Woolwich]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British Plymouth Brethren]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-vivisectionists]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Germ theory denialists]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Walter Robert Hadwen \n| image      = Walter Hadwen.png \n|birth_date  = 3 August 1854\n|birth_place = [[Woolwich]] \n|death_date  = {{d-da|27 December 1932|3 August 1854}}\n|death_place = [[Gloucester]]\n| occupation = Physician, pharmaceutical chemist, writer}}\n\n'''Walter Robert Hadwen''' MD MRCS MRCP (3 August 1854, [[Woolwich]] \u2013 27 December 1932) was a [[Gloucester]] [[general practitioner]] and pharmaceutical chemist, president of the [[British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection]] (BUAV), and an [[Anti-vaccinationists|anti-vaccination]] campaigner known for his [[germ theory denialism|denial of the germ theory of disease]].\n\n==Biography==\nHadwen began his career as a [[pharmacist]] in [[Clapham]] then [[Somerset]], then subsequently trained as a doctor at [[Bristol University]]. After qualifying, he moved to Gloucester in 1896. Hadwen was recruited as a member of BUAV by its founder and then president [[Frances Power Cobbe]] who hired a private investigator to assess his credentials (he was a [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and total abstainer, had a reputation as a \"firebrand\" orator and was held in \"high local esteem\"). She subsequently selected him as her successor.<ref>Mitchell, Sally. (2004). ''Frances Power Cobbe: Victorian Feminist, Journalist, Reformer''. University of Virginia Press. p. 360. ISBN 0-8139-2271-2</ref>\n\nHe joined the [[Plymouth Brethren]] as an adult. He was a frequent speaker for the [[National Anti-Vaccination League]]. He was also a member of the [[London Association for the Prevention of Premature Burial]] (founded in 1896).\n\nHadwen stated that the \"modern germ theory is all bosh\".<ref>{{cite journal|year=1924|title=Verdict of Manslaughter Against Dr. Hadwen by Coroner's Jury|journal=[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082605828&view=1up&seq=54|volume=83|issue=14|pages=1090}}</ref>\n\n== Manslaughter trial ==\n\nIn 1924, having applied his rejection of the [[germ theory of disease]], and his refusal to use diphtheria anti-serum produced by inoculation of animals to the treatment of Nellie Burnham, a young girl, she died and he was tried for [[manslaughter]] by criminal [[medical negligence]].<ref>[[The Times]] up to and including 30 October 1924.</ref>  He was acquitted of all charges.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1924|title=Acquittal of Dr. Hadwen|journal=[[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082605828&view=1up&seq=579|volume=83|issue=20|pages=1601}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications==\n\n* ''The Case Against Vaccination'', 1896\n*''Smallpox at Gloucester.'' A reply to Dr. Coupland\u2019s Report by Walter Hadwen, 1902. Reprinted from \"The Reformer,\" [[National Anti-Vaccination League]]: Gloucester.\n*[https://archive.org/details/debateonshouldvi00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''A Debate on Should Vivisection be Abolished?''], 1907\n*[https://archive.org/details/vivisectioncontr00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''A Vivisection Controversy''], 1911\n*[https://archive.org/details/experimentsonliv00hadw/page/n2/mode/2up ''Experiments on Living Animals, Useless and Cruel''], 1914\n*''The Difficulties of Dr. Deguerre'', 1926\n\nAbout\n*''Hadwen of Gloucester: Man, Medico, Martyr'', by Beatrice E. Kidd and M. Edith Richards, 1933, John Murray, London\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Vaccine controversy]]\n{{wikisource author}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.drhadwentrust.org/about-us/who-was-dr-hadwen Who was Dr Hadwen] Biography at Dr Hadwen Trust\n*''Frances Power Cobbe: Victorian Feminism, Journalist, Reformer'', Sally Mitchell, 2004, University of Virginia Press {{ISBN|0-8139-2271-2}}\n*''Bodily Matters: The Anti-Vaccination Movement in England, 1853-1907'', Nadja Durbach, 2005, Duke University Press, {{ISBN|0-8223-3423-2}}\n*Obituary, The Times, Saturday, 25 February 1933 John Murray, London, 1933\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soilandhealth.org/02/0201hyglibcat/020119hadwin/020119hadwenrallytalk.html SoilAndHealth.org] - 'The Case Against Vaccination', Walter Hadwen (25 January 1896)\n*[http://www.soilandhealth.org/02/0201hyglibcat/020119hadwin/020119hadwenmagazine.html SoilAndHealth.org] - ' The Fraud of Vaccination', Dr. Hadwen, ''Truth'', (3 January 1923)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hadwen, Walter}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Woolwich]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British Plymouth Brethren]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-vivisectionists]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Germ theory denialists]]\n[[Category:Vegetarianism activists]]\n", "name_user": "Psychologist Guy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected publications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hadwen"}
{"title_page": "BMW B48", "text_new": "{{short description|Turbocharged inline-four petrol engine}}\n{{Infobox automobile engine\n| name = BMW B48\n| image = BMW B48 im BMW-Museum 2018-06.jpg \n| manufacturer = [[BMW]]\n| aka =\n| production = 2014\u2013present\n| predecessor = [[BMW N20]]\n| successor =\n| configuration = [[Inline-four engine|Inline-four]]\n| displacement = {{convert|1998|cc|cuin|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| bore = {{convert|82.0|mm|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| stroke = {{convert|94.6|mm|abbr=on}}\n| block = \n| head = \n| valvetrain = [[DOHC]]\n| compression = 11:1\n| supercharger =\n| turbocharger = Single [[Turbocharger#Twin-scroll|twin-scroll]]\n| fuelsystem = [[Fuel injection#Direct injection|Direct injection]]\n| management =\n| fueltype = [[Gasoline engine|Petrol]] \n| oilsystem =\n| coolingsystem =\n| power =\n| specpower =\n| torque =\n| length =\n| width =\n| height =\n| diameter =\n| weight =\n}}\n\n[[File:BMW_B48_installed_in_a_2014_MINI_Cooper_S-_2014-08-17_17-24.jpg|thumb|right|B48 in a 2014 MINI Cooper S]]\n\nThe [[BMW]] '''B48''' is a [[turbocharged]] [[inline-four engine|inline-four]] [[gasoline|petrol]] engine which replaced the [[BMW N20]] and has been in production since 2014. It was first used in the [[Mini_Hatch#Second_generation_(R56/57)_(2006\u20132013)|F56 Mini Hatch]] and has been used in BMW applications since 2015.\n\nThe B48 is part of a modular BMW engine family of 3-cylinder ([[BMW B38|B38]]/ [[BMW B37|B37]]), 4-cylinder (B48/ [[BMW B47|B47]]) and 6-cylinder ([[BMW B58|B58]]) engines,<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW modular engines: B37, B38, B47 and B48|url=http://www.bmwblog.com/2014/05/21/bmw-modular-engines-b37-b38-b47-b48/|website=www.bmwblog.com|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> which use a displacement of {{convert|500|cc|cuin|1|abbr=on}} per cylinder.\n\n== Design ==\nCompared with its N20 predecessor, the B48 uses a more [[undersquare]] design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch out for the B's \u2013 Comparing the upcoming B48 2.0 liter turbo four-cylinder to the N20 it will replace|url=http://www.bimmerboost.com/content.php?5490-Watch-out-for-the-B-s-Comparing-the-upcoming-B48-2-0-liter-turbo-four-cylinder-to-the-N20-it-will-replace-Bore-x-stroke-specifications|website=www.bimmerboost.com|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> As per the N20, the block and head are made from [[aluminium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 BMW X1 first drive review|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/2016-bmw-x1-xdrive28i-first-drive-review|website=www.caranddriver.com|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref> Other features shared with the N20 include a twin-scroll turbocharger, [[fuel injection#Direct injection|direct injection]], [[variable valve lift]] ([[Valvetronic]]) and variable valve timing (Double [[VANOS]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW B48 Four Cylinder Turbocharged Engines|url=http://www.unixnerd.demon.co.uk/b48.html|website=www.unixnerd.demon.co.uk|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Power!!Torque!!Years\n|-\n|{{convert|135|kW|hp|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,500 [[Revolutions per minute|rpm]] ||{{convert|290|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} <br> at 1,350\u20134,250 rpm || 2016\u2013\n|-\n|{{convert|144|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 4,700\u20136,000 rpm ||{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,250\u20134,500 rpm || 2014\u2013\n|-\n|{{convert|165|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,500 rpm ||{{convert|310|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,400\u20135,000 rpm || 2016\u2013\n|-\n|{{convert|170|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,500 rpm ||{{convert|300|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,250\u20134,800 rpm || rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\u2013\n|-\n|{{convert|185|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,200\u20136,500 rpm ||{{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,450\u20134,800 rpm \n|-\n|{{convert|190|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,500 rpm ||{{convert|400|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,550\u20134,400 rpm || 2016\u2013\n|-\n|{{convert|225|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 5,000\u20136,250 rpm ||{{convert|450|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> at 1,750\u20134,500 rpm || 2019\u2013\n|}\n\n=== 135 kW version ===\nWhen combined with the electric motor, the 330e and 530e overall output is {{convert|185|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|420|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}<ref>http://www.bmw.com/com/en/newvehicles/3series/sedan/2015/showroom/technical_data.html#m=330e</ref>\n<ref>http://www.bmw.com/com/en/newvehicles/5series/sedan/2015/showroom/technical_data.html#m=530e</ref>\n\nApplications:\n* 2015\u20132019 [[BMW 3 Series (F30)|F30/F31/F34]] 320i\n* 2016\u20132018 [[BMW F30|F30]] 330e\n* 2016\u20132019 [[BMW F20|F20]] 120i\n* 2016-present [[BMW F32|F33|F36]] 420i\n* 2018\u2013present [[BMW X3 (G01)|G01]] X3 xDrive20i\n\n* 2018\u2013present [[BMW X4 (G02)|G02]] X4 xDrive20i\n* 2019\u2013present [[BMW 3 Series (G20)|G20]] 320i\n* 2019\u2013present [[BMW 3 Series (G20)|G20]] 330e\n* 2017\u2013present [[BMW 5 Series (G30)|G30]] 530e\n\n=== 144 kW version ===  \nIn the MINI Cooper S, a temporary overboost increases peak torque by {{convert|20|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} to {{convert|300|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW\u2019s new B48 2.0 litre four-cylinder TwinPower Turbo engine to produce up to 255 hp and 400 Nm|url=http://paultan.org/2014/02/25/bmws-new-2-0-litre-twinpower-turbo-engine-255hp-400nm/|website=www.paultan.org|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nApplications:\n* 2014\u2013present [[Mini Hatch#Third generation (F56) (2014)(B46: 2015-present) |F56]] MINI Cooper S<ref>{{cite web|title=MINI\u2019s Prince Engine is Dead- enter the B37 & B48|url=http://www.motoringfile.com/2013/09/05/minis-prince-engine-is-dead-enter-the-b37-b48/|website=www.motoringfile.com|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> B48A20A\n* 2015\u2013present [[BMW 2 Series (F22)|F22]] 220i\n* 2016\u2013present [[BMW X1 (F48)|F48]] X1 20i\n* 2017\u2013present [[BMW X2 (F39)|F39]] X2 sDrive20i\n*2018\u2013present [[BMW Z4 (G29)|G29]] Z4 sDrive20i\n\n=== 165 kW version ===\n* 2016\u20132019 [[BMW F20|F20]]